ickel masses are typical of other GRB-SNe,\nand greater than those of SNe Ibc that are not associated with GRBs. For GRB\n130831A / SN 2013fu, we use our well-sampled R-band light curve (LC) to\nestimate the amount of ejecta mass and the kinetic energy of the SN, finding\nthat these too are similar to other GRB-SNe. For GRB 130215A, we take advantage\nof contemporaneous optical/NIR observations to construct an optical/NIR\nbolometric LC of the afterglow. We fit the bolometric LC with the millisecond\nmagnetar model of Zhang & Meszaros (2001), which considers dipole radiation as\na source of energy injection to the forward shock powering the optical/NIR\nafterglow. Using this model we derive an initial spin period of P=12 ms and a\nmagnetic field of B=1.1 x 10^15 G, which are commensurate with those found for\nproposed magnetar central engines of other long-duration GRBs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 May 2014 11:41:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-09-05"}
