{"id":"1405.3924","submitter":"Miljenko Cemeljic Dr","authors":"Miljenko \\v{C}emelji\\'c, Nektarios Vlahakis, Kanaris Tsinganos","title":"Large resistivity in numerical simulations of radially self-similar\n  outflows","comments":"accepted in MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stu952","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the differences between an outflow in a highly-resistive\naccretion disk corona, and the results with smaller or vanishing resistivity.\nFor the first time, we determine conditions at the base of a two-dimensional\nradially self-similar outflow in the regime of very large resistivity. We\nperformed simulations using the {\\sc pluto} magnetohydrodynamics code, and\nfound three modes of solutions. The first mode, with small resistivity, is\nsimilar to the ideal-MHD solutions. In the second mode, with larger\nresistivity, the geometry of the magnetic field changes, with a \"bulge\" above\nthe super-fast critical surface. At even larger resistivities, the third mode\nof solutions sets in, in which the magnetic field is no longer collimated, but\nis pressed towards the disk. This third mode is also the final one: it does not\nchange with further increase of resistivity. These modes describe topological\nchange in a magnetic field above the accretion disk because of the uniform,\nconstant Ohmic resistivity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 May 2014 15:24:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
